What is S3?

Amazon S3 stands for Amazon Simple Storage Service.
AWS describes S3 as object storage where data is stored as objects in buckets. Buckets and objects are the core concepts. 
By default, S3 buckets and objects are private.  

Why S3 is important

S3 is one of the most widely used AWS services because it is used for:
	•	data lake storage
	•	ETL input/output
	•	backups and archiving
	•	hosting static websites
	•	application file uploads
	•	log storage
	•	ML datasets
	•	disaster recovery copies


S3 core concepts

Bucket

A bucket is a container for objects.

Example:
	•	company-raw-data
	•	my-demo-bucket
	•	project-logs-prod

Bucket names must be globally unique.


Object

An object is the actual file stored in S3.

Object contains:
	•	data
	•	key
	•	metadata
	•	version ID if versioning enabled
	•	tags
	•	storage class


Key

The full path-like name of the object.

Example:
raw/sales/2026/04/06/file1.csv

Important teaching point:
S3 is flat storage, not a real folder hierarchy. Prefixes only create folder-like organization. AWS documentation explicitly describes S3 as flat/non-hierarchical and organized using prefixes. 

Prefix

A logical grouping in object key names.

Example:
	•	raw/
	•	processed/
	•	archive/

Useful for:
	•	organizing data
	•	lifecycle rules
	•	permissions
	•	analytics partition-like layouts

Object metadata

Extra information about the object.

Examples:
	•	content type
	•	content length
	•	encryption status
	•	custom metadata


S3 architecture understanding

When you upload a file to S3:
	•	file becomes an object
	•	stored inside a bucket
	•	object is identified by key
	•	access is controlled by IAM, bucket policy, ACLs, and block public access settings
	•	optional versioning, encryption, replication, lifecycle can apply

S3 storage classes

AWS offers multiple storage classes, and objects can be stored in different classes depending on access pattern, cost, and availability needs.  ￼

Important ones to teach:

S3 Standard

For frequently accessed data.

Use cases:
	•	active application files
	•	hot data
	•	frequently used reports

S3 Intelligent-Tiering

Automatically moves objects based on access patterns to help optimize costs.  ￼

S3 Standard-IA

For infrequently accessed but quickly needed data.

 S3 One Zone-IA

Cheaper, but stored in one Availability Zone.

S3 Glacier Instant Retrieval

Archive-style, but fast retrieval for some use cases.

S3 Glacier Flexible Retrieval

For archive data.

S3 Glacier Deep Archive

Very low cost long-term archive.


